note_alerts:
Caution Ruts on runway; Land to the North and Takeoff to the South due to terrain.
1- You must land in the first 1/3 of the runway or you will run out of runway at the top, the top is not forgiving as there is a berm and a ditch there.
2- If you are not comfortable with the approach you must abort early as the only go around option is to the pilots right with rising terrain.

Runway(s) 35 has non standard hand traffic.
note_default:
Saline Valley Warm Springs Airfield, commonly known as the Chicken Strip is a non-towered dirt airstrip not depicted on an FAA Sectional chart. The airstrip provides general aviation fly-in access to the Saline Valley hot springs in Death Valley National Park.
RAF to Partner with NPS on Chicken Strip Maintenance

The Recreational Aviation Foundation (RAF) and Death Valley National Park officially signed a five-year cooperative maintenance agreement for the Chicken Strip in Saline Valley. The Memorandum of Understanding (MOU), dated October 18, also renews the established maintenance agreement at Furnace Creek Airport and Stovepipe Wells Airstrip.

The RAF has proven that this partnership works since our original 2008 MOU, RAF Chairman John McKenna said. The National Park Service recognizes us as a valuable contributor toward safely ensuring aircraft very low impact form of access to the Park, he added.

Article I of the document concludes: The NPS benefits from the efficient operation of these sites as a result of the maintenance of safer airstrips for use by the Park and the public.

The agreement names the RAF, and specifically RAF California Liaison Rick Lach, as sole contact with the Park. Lach has mustered volunteers over the years to assist with the re-opening of the gravel strip after seasonal washouts, and helped provide maintenance every autumn. We have no problem rounding up twenty or so volunteers from all over California and Arizona for a work weekend, he explained.

Rick has proven that we are folks who are willing to invest sweat equity for the opportunity to use these three dispersed airstrips,
















































































































































































RAF President Bill McGlynn said.

The NPS will provide a drag to smooth Chicken Strip, with the RAF providing a pickup to pull it and a tractor with bucket or blade, if necessary and all hand or power tools needed. Furnace Creek and Stovepipe Wells are paved, so the RAF is only expected to help maintain runway markers and tiedowns, and remove vegetation if requested by Park officials.

RAF to Partner with NPS on Chicken Strip Maintenance

The Recreational Aviation Foundation (RAF) and Death Valley National Park officially signed a five-year cooperative maintenance agreement for the Chicken Strip in Saline Valley. The Memorandum of Understanding (MOU), dated October 18, also renews the established maintenance agreement at Furnace Creek Airport and Stovepipe Wells Airstrip.

The RAF has proven that this partnership works since our original 2008 MOU, RAF Chairman John McKenna said. The National Park Service recognizes us as a valuable contributor toward safely ensuring aircraft very low impact form of access to the Park, he added.

Article I of the document concludes: The NPS benefits from the efficient operation of these sites as a result of the maintenance of safer airstrips for use by the Park and the public.

The agreement names the RAF, and specifically RAF California Liaison Rick Lach, as sole contact with the Park. Lach has mustered volunteers over the years to assist with the re-opening of the gravel strip after seasonal washouts, and helped provide maintenance every autumn. We have no problem rounding up twenty or so volunteers from all over California and Arizona for a work weekend, he explained.

Rick has proven that we are folks who are willing to invest sweat equity for the opportunity to use these three dispersed airstrips,
















































































































































































RAF President Bill McGlynn said.

The NPS will provide a drag to smooth Chicken Strip, with the RAF providing a pickup to pull it and a tractor with bucket or blade, if necessary and all hand or power tools needed. Furnace Creek and Stovepipe Wells are paved, so the RAF is only expected to help maintain runway markers and tiedowns, and remove vegetation if requested by Park officials.

This airport has noise abatement areas, view runways page for more info.
note_default:
This airfield is only 3 miles from Chrystal Bridges Museum. Although there are obstacles on either end, it's easily long enough for most aircraft. The approach to runway 10 has a gap cut in the trees near the end of the runway if the pilot is willing to make an abrupt low level turn.
Bring your own tie downs.
The Louise Thaden/Bentonville Airport is located just 4nm to the south west. Maintenance, fuel and courtesy cars are available there. Sugar Creek is used for flight school training on a regular basis, so be especially alert when on the runway.
Sugar Creek lays partially inside Rogers/Carter Field (KROG) Class D airspace. Through an agreement with the Rogers tower we have permission to enter and exit the pattern at Sugar Creek from the west without making radio contact with the tower. Pilots must remain below 2,500' MSL and remain within 0.5 NM of the airfield to the east. Pilots transitioning east from Sugar Creek are obliged to contact the tower. West transitions do not need to contact the tower so long as the aircraft remains below 2,500' MSL. Be aware that the outer ring of KXNA's Class C airspace also overlays Sugar Creek. The floor is 2,900' MSL.

Caution, bring your own food and water. Bring extra water.
Caution, no cell phone service
Caution, no restroom facilities. Bring a shovel for #2. Burn or pack out your used TP.
Pack it in. Pack it out. Leave no trace.
Bring your own firewood. Be mindful of fire danger. Use only established rock fire rings. Extinguish campfire by flooding with water before you leave, even if it looks like the fire is out. Dig out the campfire ash residue and bury it away from the camping area to leave the fire pit clean for the next pilot.
Leave the camping area the same or better than the way you found it.
Caution, high density altitude
* The Spiral Jetty airstrip is on the eastern shore of the Great Salt Lake
* Hike 1.5 miles south on dirt road and or view by air the Spiral Jetty land art, created in 1970
* Hike 2 miles northwest to see historic Rozel Point airway beacon
* Refer to the links to learn more about the Spiral Jetty and the Great Salt Lake
* By air, you can see the remnants of one of the oldest oil fields in Utah. It is about 0.3 mi southwest of the Spiral Jetty land art and 2 miles by air southwest of the Spiral Jetty airstrip.

contact: {'name': 'Frank Aebly', 'email': 'frank.aebly@usda.gov', 'address': 'Upper Lake, CA 95485', 'webSite': None, 'phone': '707-275-1401', 'mobile': None, 'cityStateZip': None, 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'phone', 'name': 'Phone'}}

{'alert': [{'text': 'General practice is to Land RWY 1 and depart RWY 19.

RWY 1: 36 Ft trees 600 ft from runway, 125 ft right of centerline, 16:1 slope to clear
RWY 19: 800 ft hill, 800 ft from runway, 1:1 slope to clear
Two roads crossing the runway, watch for traffic.

', 'type': 'alert', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-alert.svg?v1'}], 'default': [{'id': 'a1050390-f8f6-4077-a2f3-c867108ed001', 'text': 'Gravelly Valley is an excellent area for airplane camping and is surrounded by wooded hills and the Lake Pillsbury reservoir on the South end.. The runway is a USFS airstrip developed for large aircraft, so can feel much larger than most dirt strips. While there are private campgrounds and cabins nearby, the strip is relatively isolated from other activity. It is a peaceful place where one can fly to and just enjoy being outside, nearly year round.

There is a large Elk population in the region, so be aware of wildlife on the runway. Seasonal weather can result low clouds over surrounding ridges and may result in a delayed departure or arrival. Plan ahead for fuel, as Gravelly can be clear but other nearby airports (including the adjacent Sacramento Valley) can be fogged in.

note_alerts:
General practice is to Land RWY 1 and depart RWY 19.

RWY 1: 36 Ft trees 600 ft from runway, 125 ft right of centerline, 16:1 slope to clear
RWY 19: 800 ft hill, 800 ft from runway, 1:1 slope to clear
Two roads crossing the runway, watch for traffic.

RWY 1 Landable after road crossing on south end. About 2600 feet between South road crossing and middle road crossing (near windsock).
note_default:
Gravelly Valley is an excellent area for airplane camping and is surrounded by wooded hills and the Lake Pillsbury reservoir on the South end.. The runway is a USFS airstrip developed for large aircraft, so can feel much larger than most dirt strips. While there are private campgrounds and cabins nearby, the strip is relatively isolated from other activity. It is a peaceful place where one can fly to and just enjoy being outside, nearly year round.

There is a large Elk population in the region, so be aware of wildlife on the runway. Seasonal weather can result low clouds over surrounding ridges and may result in a delayed departure or arrival. Plan ahead for fuel, as Gravelly can be clear but other nearby airports (including the adjacent Sacramento Valley) can be fogged in.

Undeveloped “shooting range” at the NE end of the field

The runway is a USFS airstrip developed for large aircraft, so can feel much larger than most dirt strips. While there are private campgrounds and cabins nearby, the strip is relatively isolated from other activity. It is a peaceful place where one can fly to and just enjoy being outside, nearly year round.

There is a large Elk population in the region, so be aware of wildlife on the runway. Seasonal weather can result low clouds over surrounding ridges and may result in a delayed departure or arrival. Plan ahead for fuel, as Gravelly can be clear but other nearby airports (including the adjacent Sacramento Valley) can be fogged in.

Undeveloped “shooting range” at the NE end of the field

note_alerts:
Non standard canyon type approaches required

Departure from runway 10 not recommended due to uphill slope and high terrain at departure end.

Pilots should fly in the canyons to the west or to the northeast to come and go from Happy Canyon. Any other direction is not practical due to high terrain. If an aircraft needs to circle to gain altitude, it is recommended to circle north of runway 10/28 due to terrain. There is descending terrain to the west of Happy Canyon airstrip

Runway(s) 18 has right hand traffic.
Runway(s) 28 has non standard hand traffic.
note_default:

Great airstrip for camping & dark sky stargazing.

Airstrip is leased by UBCP. UBCP requests that no man-made artifacts (drill bits, tools, old household items, etc.) be removed. Emergency water and runway grading tools are in the mining shack.

Attacked by Geronimo on two occasions, and the resting place of outlaw Bill Johnson, buried in the old cemetery near the south end of the runway, its history is incredible. The 1950s log cabin lodge and bunk house still stand with the RAF and APA working with the USFS to preserve and restore the lodge. The lodge serves as shelter and sleeping quarters for those who prefer 4 walls to a tent.

Triple Tree boasts a replica of Monet Garden in Giverny, France, separate Men and Women shower houses, 6 miles of hiking trails, 3 Lakes, Enoree River on the Southern border, a collection of historical aircraft, outdoor patio overlooking lake, and a restored WWII-era Control Tower. During events they have a small general store that sells basic necessities.
Town of Enoree SC is 4 miles south.
Obstacles: two churches, 2,000' north DO NOT overfly on Sunday am.

Operations: daylight to dusk.

note_alerts:
Mexican Mountain is with-in a Wilderness Study Area (WSA) which means:

- NO mechanized equipment (except aircraft), NO bikes, chainsaws etc.
- NO new firepits, use the ones there and bury your ashes.
- NO trash, you must pack out ALL you bring in
- DO bury your "number two" and either burn your toliet paper or pack it out
- Don't use the bathroom with-in 100 ft of a waterway.

Please follow these rules and keep this a special place for all of us!

Runway(s) 11,29 has non standard hand traffic.
note_default:
Trees at Approach end of Rwy 11, use overrun on Rwy 29 for obstacle clearance only. Best approach is Rwy 29.Rwy 11 preferred takeoff runway
San Rafael river boarders the runway and has been known to flood the South end of the runway. Plan well, be careful and enjoy one of Utah's number one backcountry strip! Mexican Mountain has it all, remote, no roads, no service, no port-a-lets. It offers primitive camping, beautiful canyons, rock art, solitude and history. It's not for everyone, short demanding runway and can be unforgiving.
Significant negotiation and work go into protecting backcountry airstrips and trust is earned through fulfilling out commitments to the land managers and owners. Honoring these agreements can go a long way towards these efforts, and even opening new airstrips. A few rogue pilots can destroy this trust and set our backcountry efforts backwards for years.

Please leave it better than you found it.

title: Trigger Gap
contact: {'name': 'Harper Goodwin', 'email': 'harpergoodwin@gmail.com', 'address': None, 'webSite': None, 'phone': None, 'mobile': '817-938-3334', 'cityStateZip': None, 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'mobile', 'name': 'Mobile'}}
notes:
{'alert': [{'text': 'Trigger Gap was designed to be a "Destination" airstrip, land, get out and enjoy lunch or camp. To help with noise issues, Please DO NOT use for training flights, conduct multiple landings and take off\'s or fly low over the area. Also, please land on RWY 28 as the primary runway when conditions allow. When taking off on Rwy 28 depart with the lowest power setting required and initially turn SW. DO NOT depart RWY 28 & turn immediately to the North, these procedures greatly help to reduce noise complaints. note_alerts:
Trigger Gap was designed to be a "Destination" airstrip, land, get out and enjoy lunch or camp. To help with noise issues, Please DO NOT use for training flights, conduct multiple landings and take off's or fly low over the area. Also, please land on RWY 28 as the primary runway when conditions allow. When taking off on Rwy 28 depart with the lowest power setting required and initially turn SW. DO NOT depart RWY 28 & turn immediately to the North, these procedures greatly help to reduce noise complaints. See the Map Tab for more details.
Note - RWY 10 is RIGHT HAND PATTERN, see details on runway tab.

Use Caution when taxing off runway for possible "animal' holes
This airport has noise abatement areas, view runways page for more info.
Runway(s) 10 has right hand traffic.

Strong winds are common, especially in the afternoon.
Runway(s) 13,31 has non standard hand traffic.
note_defaultThis airstrip is Closed from October 1st till June 1st annually.
Camping is not allowed on the airfield, one must camp at designated campground which requires carrying gear off field.

note_alerts:
Pilots landing at Las Trancas Airfield must have individually requested, received and acknowledged the current Briefing through the Airfield.Guide. This Briefing is advisory in nature and does not replace the pilot's responsibility to use sound judgment regarding level of skill, experience and aircraft suitability. Pilots should be thoroughly familiar with mountain flying techniques, slow flight and safe procedures for primitive airstrip operations. Las Trancas is small (800' x 25') and rough. This is a "back country" strip, at the California coast.
Caution; wind shear and rotor on short approach.
Steep 100ft cliffs on three sides, resulting in low-level turbulence and wind shear, including a rotor at the approach end of 32, any time the wind is blowing.
The strip is adjacent to a Monterey Bay Marine Sanctuary designated area with a 1000' flight restriction (see chart) and Big Basin
State Park, with the popular Waddell Beach just to the north. Remain close to the strip when in the pattern.
The briefing is required.
Runway(s) 14 has right hand traffic.
note_default:
RW32 Left Hand Traffic, usually is favored based on winds. RWY 14 (Right hand traffic) is useable in a south wind. It is downhill past the halfway mark in this direction.

Parking - Space for a couple aircraft on compacted ground exists near the hangar. Remaining parking is in mowed ice plant in sandy soil. Recommend visual inspection before use. Big tires helpful. Bring your own tie-downs

contact: {'name': 'Lupita A.  Wisener', 'email': 'wisenerairport@aol.com', 'address': 'Mineola, TX 75773', 'webSite': None, 'phone': '903-569-1929', 'mobile': None, 'cityStateZip': None, 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'phone', 'name': 'Phone'}}
notes:
{'alert': [], 'default': [{'id': '76a15a4f-1d07-496b-b97d-091a2d7ab24c', 'text': "Airport identifier 3F9 UNICOM 122.8
\nEstabished in 1917, and operated by the same family since 1926, Mineola-Wisener Field is the oldest privately owned public use airport in Texas. Famous aviators who have visited Wisener Field include Wiley Post, 'Slats' Rogers, Tommy Grace, and Fay Lucille Cox. Famous visitors to Wisener Field have included Senators Phil Graham, Kay Baley Hutcherson and then Senator, later President, Lyndon B. Johnson. Starting with a small grass field and one Curtiss JN4C, Wisener Field now has a 3203 x 40 paved and lighted runway and is proud to be the homebase of over seventy aircraft. We offer 24 hour self-service 100LL avgas and provide access to A&P, Flight Instructor and Aircraft Rental services. We provide low cost hangar rental rates for all aircraft types- business, personal, antiques, warbirds, homebuilts, ultra-lights and helicopters. Come help us continue to make history. Remember, we are privately owned and really appreciate your business!", 'type': 'airportHistory', 'position': 1, 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-history.svg?v1', 'editVersion': 1, 'createdAt': '2020-06-02T00:55:25+00:00', 'updatedAt': '2020-06-02T00:55:25+00:00'}]}

• Wentworth Aerodrome (WAD) is located at the beginning of the White Mountains in central New Hampshire. It's a 1,750'x125' grass strip with decent approaches and departures.
  • The hangar has WiFi and hot showers. Contact the owner for the WiFi password.
  • Bicycles are available for use on the adjoining railed or to ride to town across the wooden covered bridge.
  • Biking is available on the rails-to-trails rail bed nearby.
  • Swimming is available at the river a short walk away.
  • An 8x10 cabin is available by permission for camping. It has two cots, a refrigerator, wood stove and electricity.
  • The owner suggests this airfield is best served by taildragger or C-182 aircraft and above, operated by a competent short field pilot.
  • The width of the runway makes it appear shorter than it actually is.

  • The hangar has WiFi and hot showers. Contact the owner for the WiFi password.

  • Swimming is available at the river a short walk away.

  • The width of the runway makes it appear shorter than it actually is.

Call the owner for permission and fill out the safety briefing/liability release must be reviewed and sent to owner before landing.
The traffic pattern is on the beach side of the runway Right traffic for Rwy 10, Left traffic for Rwy 28.

Please do not overfly the school to the East

aircraft not recommended.

  • Announce your position and intentions at least 10 miles from the airfield on 122.9.

  • Beware of the drainage ditch separating the runway and the tiedown area.
  • Camp in the campsites or under your wing. The state park collects $5 per night per aircraft camping fee.
  • Campers can use the shower blocks in the adjacent campground. Park staff will deliver firewood and ice if requested.
  • There are many restaurants, shops, and stores in town. note_alerts:
There are a few towers, wind generators, tall factory, and even a grain silo that is in-line with runway 29 final 2/3 of a mile out. These are not hard to avoid as long as a normal approach is used but all pilots should be aware of these.

Part of the runway is used for a fairly active RC flying group. They normally monitor 122.9 and pause for in bound aircraft. Just be aware
Runway(s) 29 has right hand traffic.

Fishing allowed in the small pond across the runway from the hangar. Not the one across the gravel road.

Dyersville attractions:

note_alerts:
The primary take-off and no-wind runway is 10 and is parallel with the highway and powerline to the immediate south.

The crosswind runway 5/23 has an upslope when landing to the south.

If winds dictate landing on the crosswind runway 5/23, be cautious as the upslope and power line on the south end usually make this a poor
choice for take-off or go-around.

Runways with right hand traffic: 05, 28. See the Runways tab for more information.

Take offs are suggested, winds permitting, on runway 5 (downhill) or runway 10 (downhill). If taking off on runway 28 be advised the terrain climbs for the next 1 mile after departure and departure path will overfly the town. Runway 23 is not recommended for takeoff of unless aircraft is very STOL capable due to upslope and power line obstacles.
Runway(s) 5 has right hand traffic.
Runway(s) 28 has non standard hand traffic.
note_default:
Visitors to the airstrip can access a gas station via a short walk, or enjoy restaurants, bars and lodging by walking about two miles over the hill into picturesque Randsburg with its surviving original facades and buildings.

The annual September Western Days Celebration brings live music, vendors and crowds. Visitors can pan for gold and witness staged gun fights.

There are many abandoned and functioning mines in the immediate area.
Runways with right hand traffic: 05 and 28. See the Runways tab for more information.

* By air, you can see the remnants of one of the oldest oil fields in Utah. It is about 0.3 mi southwest of the Spiral Jetty land art and 2 miles by air southwest of the Spiral Jetty airstrip.

note_default:
Thaden Field is under the XNA Class C shelf. The base of the outer shelf is 2,900' MSL but approach control requests that our operations remain at 2,500' MSL or below. Please note that the inner ring, which begins at the surface, is only a few miles west of Thaden Field. Please remain clear of the Class C airspace unless you are in communication with Razorback Approach on 126.6.
Simultaneous operations on runways 17/35 and 18/36 are not permitted.

For current turf runway status Click Here.


Louise Thaden Field in Bentonville is the perfect jumping off spot for flying in the Ozarks, and is the home of FLY OZ. With a new facility including a restaurant and a flying club, it's a great place to plan your adventure. The airport is located next to a lake and public park with a fantastic viewing deck for grading landings on either the asphalt or turf runway.
Thaden Field has a full service restaurant in the FBO as well as restaurants and hotels nearby. Jet-A and 100LL full service fuel and maintenance are available. If you'd like to fish in the adjoining lake, fishing supplies and equipment can be purchased at the front desk. Rental canoes are also available. Showers, restrooms, and a pilot rest area can be found in the FBO, along with courtesy and rent cars. The Oz1 Flying Club offers guest memberships for access to the club lounge and drink discounts.

note_defaultThaden Field is under the XNA Class C shelf. The base of the outer shelf is 2,900' MSL but approach control requests that our operations remain at 2,500' MSL or below. Please note that the inner ring, which begins at the surface, is only a few miles west of Thaden Field. Please remain clear of the Class C airspace unless you are in communication with Razorback Approach on 126.6.
Simultaneous operations on runways 17/35 and 18/36 are not permitted.

note_alerts:
* Announce your position and intentions early and be aware of possible traffic at both Minam Lodge and Reds Horse Ranch.
* No straight in landings are allowed.
* Use caution overflying Reds Horse Ranch.
Contact the owner before use
Runway(s) 33 has right hand traffic.
note_default:
1) Airfield is located in a rugged, narrow canyon surrounded by steeply raising terrain. The mountains immediately adjacent rise quickly to 1400 feet above the airfield elevation.
2. Density altitude must be considered, plan accordingly
4. Approach the airfield from 8 to 10 miles to the North and fly up the Minam River, keeping to the right of the river. Be aware of other aircraft that may be flying down river.
5. Overfly the airfield to check for wildlife, aircraft, equipment or people.
6. Winds permitting, generally land to the South and depart to the North.
7. There is no cell phone or VHF radio reception within the canyon. You must close your flight plan before arriving.

note_alerts:
Fremont Island Upper airstrip has high/rising terrain at the departure end of runway 33. Also, there is a knob of high terrain with a weather pole on top at the approach end of runway 33. You do not land or depart over these two features

Runway is on a ridge that slopes up at both ends with downward sloping terrain on both sides.
note_default:
Bring a chair and a sack lunch while you sit back and enjoy the spectacular panoramic view of the Great Salt Lake and the snow capped mountains. Listen to the quiet rustling of the breeze and soak up the calming serenity of this backcountry airstrip jewel. Gnats can be pesky in the spring.

Hike to the cross that Kit Carson carved into the rock on the highest peak on Fremont Island.
The airstrips at Fremont Island are managed by the UBCP in accordance with a Memorandum of Understanding between the Utah DNR - Sovereign Lands Department and Utah State Aeronautics. Because of the nature of the land, there are a few rules that must be adhered to and pilots are required to review these rules prior to departing for the island:

No fires of any kind are permitted
No fireworks or explosive items
No discharge of firearms or hunting

No fires of any kind are permitted
No fireworks or explosive items
No discharge of firearms or hunting

contact: {'name': 'Ron Brewster', 'email': None, 'address': 'Bakersfield, CA 93308-7026', 'webSite': 'http://www.kernvalleyairport.com/', 'phone': '661-391-1824', 'mobile': None, 'cityStateZip': None, 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'phone', 'name': 'Phone'}}
notes:

Kern Valley Airport is surrounded by the Southern Sierras with peaks from 6500FT to over 10,000FT. You should plan to be on the ground by sunset.

Cafe - Open for breakfast and lunch 7:00AM to 3:00PM seven days a week.', 'type': 'airportUse', 'position': 1, 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-airplane.svg?v1', 'editVersion': 1, 'createdAt': '2020-06-09T17:50:09+00:00', 'updatedAt': '2020-06-09T17:50:09+00:00'}, {'id': '929b731b-3143-4c9b-9696-e96dd7e956a0', 'text': 'No constraining obstacles. The airport has a very well maintained lawn campground with hot showers, port-a-potty toilets and running water (sink and faucet).

The facilities include a cafe at the airport which serves breakfast and lunch, closing for dinner unless for special events

There is a nearby town that is roughly 2 miles away from the airport parking area - one can walk or borrow the crew car (when available) to access the town which has numerable restaurants, bars, grocery stores, and hotels.

There are a number of outfitters in town that provide mountain biking and rafting shuttle services as well as guided trips to the Sierra backcountry.

The Kern (a wild and scenic river known for exceptional white water rafting) is accessible from the airport. It is stocked with hungry trout.

There is a nearby town that is roughly 2 miles away from the airport parking area - one can walk or borrow the crew car (when available) to access the town which has numerable restaurants, bars, grocery stores, and hotels.

There are a number of outfitters in town that provide mountain biking and rafting shuttle services as well as guided trips to the Sierra backcountry.

The Kern (a wild and scenic river known for exceptional white water rafting) is accessible from the airport. It is stocked with hungry trout.
Lake Isabella (2 miles south of the airport) provides further recreational opportunities.

title: Ryan Field
contact: {'name': 'Tricia McKenna', 'email': None, 'address': None, 'webSite': 'http://theraf.org', 'phone': None, 'mobile': '406-570-5398', 'cityStateZip': 'Bozeman, MT 59715', 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'mobile', 'name': 'Mobile'}}
notes:
{'alert': [{'text': 'Ryan Field is open to pilots with the requirement that each pilot request and receive a current safety briefing from this website (Airfield.Guide). Look at the "Briefing Tab" for this airstrip.
', 'type': 'caution', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-alert.svg?v1'}, {'text': 'Glacier National Park is now requiring a reservation to drive Going to the Sun Road. See Links for more details', 'type': 'alert', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-alert.svg?v1'}, {'text': 'The briefing is required.', 'type': 'briefing', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-briefing.svg?v1'}], 'default': [{'id': 'adb9ec6c-2dc8-4af0-a75c-eed26624f2a2', 'text': '
  • Water: Drinking water is available at the pilot shelter. During the winter months there is a frost free hydrant located Northeast corner of lower tiedown area on the east side of the runway.
  • Food Storage: This is bear country. All food must be stored in bear proof locations. There are three steel food storage containers available. Leave no garbage out.
  • Bear Spray is the best personal protection in bear country.
  • Firewood: The wood in the pilots' shelter is for the cook stove. Use other wood for the fire ring outside. No other camp fires are allowed.
  • Garbage: Either take your garbage with you when you fly out or dispose of it at a garbage container site. A disposal site is located about a mile east of the town of Hungry Horse on the south side of Highway 2. As you are driving from West Glacier to Hungry Horse it will be on your left just after the Packers Roost Bar.
  • Ben Ryan had an interesting career as, first, a WW II military aviator and, second, a petroleum geologist. To read Ben's autobiography click here.
  • Phone Service: There is cell coverage depending on the carrier (Verizon is fine; T-Mobile doesn't get much). A local phone book is in the non-food steel storage cabinet in the pilot shelter.
  • Courtesy Car: The RAF has a courtesy car available on a first come, first served basis. The car is not available during the winter. note_alerts:
Ryan Field is open to pilots with the requirement that each pilot request and receive a current safety briefing from this website (Airfield.Guide). Look at the "Briefing Tab" for this airstrip.

Glacier National Park is now requiring a reservation to drive Going to the Sun Road. See Links for more details
The briefing is required.
note_default:
• Water: Drinking water is available at the pilot shelter. During the winter months there is a frost free hydrant located Northeast corner of lower tiedown area on the east side of the runway.
  • Food Storage: This is bear country. All food must be stored in bear proof locations. There are three steel food storage containers available. Leave no garbage out.
  • Bear Spray is the best personal protection in bear country.
  • Firewood: The wood in the pilots' shelter is for the cook stove. Use other wood for the fire ring outside. No other camp fires are allowed.
  • Garbage: Either take your garbage with you when you fly out or dispose of it at a garbage container site. A disposal site is located about a mile east of the town of Hungry Horse on the south side of Highway 2. As you are driving from West Glacier to Hungry Horse it will be on your left just after the Packers Roost Bar.
  • Ben Ryan had an interesting career as, first, a WW II military aviator and, second, a petroleum geologist. To read Ben's autobiography click here.
  • Phone Service: There is cell coverage depending on the carrier (Verizon is fine; T-Mobile doesn't get much). A local phone book is in the non-food steel storage cabinet in the pilot shelter.
  • Courtesy Car: The RAF has a courtesy car available on a first come, first served basis. The car is not available during the winter. Instructions are in the vehicle log book located in the visitor sign-in mail box. We ask that you only use the car for short trips to town to get supplies etc. Please don't take the car for a full day adventure trip. That leaves everyone else walking!
  • Walking to West Glacier: One mile walking trail through the forest. Details and map located in the pilot shelter.
  • Camper Cabins: Four camper cabins are available for use. For more information and to view the cabin reservation calendar, go to the Links Tab, select Ryan Cabins and scroll down to Cabin information to reserve a cabin
    All operations should remain south of the Flathead River.
    Seasonal weather station(May thru October) Click Here
    Text M or C to 406-595-7345 for METAR or Decoded weather

note_alerts:
Rwy 10/28 has a lot of large rocks and brush. This runway is useable only by big tire, bush-wheel equipped, aircraft

Rwy 16/34 is covered with medium height bunch grasses and is a rough in places, but reasonably good immediately north of the vehicle track

The first 400 feet from the approach end of Rwy 16 is quite rocky and rough. If landing on Rwy 16, touchdown well south of the windsock.

There is about 1,400 feet useable on Rwy 34 between the vehicle track crossing the runway and the windsock.

If the winds allow, it is recommended to land Rwy 34 and depart Rwy 16
note_default:
No fires are permitted in the summer
The strip is about 2300ft long at about 5000 MSL. It's 170 statute miles from KHIO. It's on USFS land in the Umatilla National Forest. I contacted the District Ranger and he said it was OK to use the strip but it is not maintained.

I landed there on 4/23/19. The main runway (34-16) still has a little water on it so I landed on the shorter runway 28 that has an uphill slope and better drainage. 28 was pretty rough for 800X6's. I kept my speed up until I got to the runway intersection to avoid dropping a tire in a hole.

The main runway is relatively flat and smooth. 6 X 6:00 tires should be OK if rough field techniques are used. The approaches are clear from both directions. 34-16 has tires marking the ends but they could use a new coat of white paint. There is an ATV trail that crosses the runway but it doesn't cause a problem. There is a hole in runway 34 near the ATV trail crossing on the left edge. We should fill it next time we come.

There are reasonable camping areas near the the runway intersection. A wind sock pole is located at runway intersection but the sock is gone. I heard a report that one was installed early 2020. I've got a feeling bug repellent would be a good idea later in the year.

If the winds allow, it is recommended to land Rwy 34 and depart Rwy 16
note_defaultNo fires are permitted in the summer
The strip is about 2300ft long at about 5000 MSL. It's 170 statute miles from KHIO. It's on USFS land in the Umatilla National Forest. I contacted the District Ranger and he said it was OK to use the strip but it is not maintained.

I landed there on 4/23/19. The main runway (34-16) still has a little water on it so I landed on the shorter runway 28 that has an uphill slope and better drainage. 28 was pretty rough for 800X6's. I kept my speed up until I got to the runway intersection to avoid dropping a tire in a hole.

The main runway is relatively flat and smooth. 6 X 6:00 tires should be OK if rough field techniques are used. The approaches are clear from both directions. 34-16 has tires marking the ends but they could use a new coat of white paint. There is an ATV trail that crosses the runway but it doesn't cause a problem. There is a hole in runway 34 near the ATV trail crossing on the left edge. We should fill it next time we come.

There are reasonable camping areas near the the runway intersection. A wind sock pole is located at runway intersection but the sock is gone. I heard a report that one was installed early 2020. I've got a feeling bug repellent would be a good idea later in the year.

title: Chicken Strip
contact: {'name': 'Rick Lach (RAF)', 'email': None, 'address': None, 'webSite': None, 'phone': None, 'mobile': '661-345-7755', 'cityStateZip': None, 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'mobile', 'name': 'Mobile'}}
notes:
{'alert': [{'text': 'Caution Ruts on runway; Land to the North and Takeoff to the South due to terrain.
1- You must land in the first 1/3 of the runway or you will run out of runway at the top, the top is not forgiving as there is a berm and a ditch there.

', 'type': 'alert', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-alert.svg?v1'}, {'text': 'Runway(s) 35 has non standard hand traffic.', 'type': 'nonStandardRunwayTraffic', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-non-standard-traffic.svg?v1'}], 'default': [{'id': 'bf7f13de-8b18-476c-b030-0b703af274d1', 'text': 'Saline Valley Warm Springs Airfield, commonly known as the Chicken Strip is a non-towered dirt airstrip not depicted on an FAA Sectional chart. The airstrip provides general aviation fly-in access to the Saline Valley hot springs in Death Valley National Park.', 'type': 'airportHistory', 'position': 1, 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-history.svg?v1', 'editVersion': 1, 'createdAt': '2019-12-13T14:15:37+00:00', 'updatedAt': '2019-12-13T14:15:37+00:00'}, {'id': '31cdeef6-e378-4d0b-9077-e13047d7e749', 'text': 'RAF to Partner with NPS on Chicken Strip Maintenance

The Recreational Aviation Foundation (RAF) and Death Valley National Park officially signed a five-year cooperative maintenance agreement for the Chicken Strip in Saline Valley. The Memorandum of Understanding (MOU), dated October 18, also renews the established maintenance agreement at Furnace Creek Airport and Stovepipe Wells Airstrip.

The RAF has proven that this partnership works since our original 2008 MOU, RAF Chairman John McKenna said. The National Park Service recognizes us as a valuable contributor toward safely ensuring aircraft very low impact form of access to the Park, he added.

Article I of the document concludes: The NPS benefits from the efficient operation of these sites as a result of the maintenance of safer airstrips for use by the Park and the public.

The agreement names the RAF, and specifically RAF California Liaison Rick Lach, as sole contact with the Park. Lach has mustered volunteers over the years to assist with the re-opening of the gravel strip after seasonal washouts, and helped provide maintenance every autumn. We have no problem rounding up twenty or so volunteers from all over California and Arizona for a work weekend, he explained.

Rick has proven that we are folks who are willing to invest sweat equity for the opportunity to use these three dispersed airstrips,
















































































































































































RAF President Bill McGlynn said.

The NPS will provide a drag to smooth Chicken Strip, with the RAF providing a pickup to pull it and a tractor with bucket or blade, if necessary and all hand or power tools needed. Furnace Creek and Stovepipe Wells are paved, so the RAF is only expected to help maintain runway markers and tiedowns, and remove vegetation if requested by Park officials.', 'type': 'information', 'position': 3, 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-info.svg?v1', 'editVersion': 1, 'createdAt': '2019-12-13T14:25:33+00:00', 'updatedAt': '2019-12-13T14:25:33+00:00'}]}
note_alerts:
Caution Ruts on runway; Land to the North and Takeoff to the South due to terrain.
1- You must land in the first 1/3 of the runway or you will run out of runway at the top, the top is not forgiving as there is a berm and a ditch there.
2- If you are not comfortable with the approach you must abort early as the only go around option is to the pilots right with rising terrain.

Runway(s) 35 has non standard hand traffic.
note_default:
Saline Valley Warm Springs Airfield, commonly known as the Chicken Strip is a non-towered dirt airstrip not depicted on an FAA Sectional chart. The airstrip provides general aviation fly-in access to the Saline Valley hot springs in Death Valley National Park.
RAF to Partner with NPS on Chicken Strip Maintenance

The Recreational Aviation Foundation (RAF) and Death Valley National Park officially signed a five-year cooperative maintenance agreement for the Chicken Strip in Saline Valley. The Memorandum of Understanding (MOU), dated October 18, also renews the established maintenance agreement at Furnace Creek Airport and Stovepipe Wells Airstrip.

The RAF has proven that this partnership works since our original 2008 MOU, RAF Chairman John McKenna said. The National Park Service recognizes us as a valuable contributor toward safely ensuring aircraft very low impact form of access to the Park, he added.

Article I of the document concludes: The NPS benefits from the efficient operation of these sites as a result of the maintenance of safer airstrips for use by the Park and the public.

The agreement names the RAF, and specifically RAF California Liaison Rick Lach, as sole contact with the Park. Lach has mustered volunteers over the years to assist with the re-opening of the gravel strip after seasonal washouts, and helped provide maintenance every autumn. We have no problem rounding up twenty or so volunteers from all over California and Arizona for a work weekend, he explained.

Rick has proven that we are folks who are willing to invest sweat equity for the opportunity to use these three dispersed airstrips,

notes: {'alert': [], 'default': [{'id': '56066856-49ae-440d-ad3f-719a601e9aea', 'text': 'From Jim Hanson, the airport manager, \'We are somewhat unique here in Albert Lea.  The airport is almost within town - the west side has \'quiet water\' (Minnesotan for \'shallow\') used by canoes and Kayaks.  We have 7 food places within 4 blocks, two grocery stores,  and an auto parts store - we are adjacent to a golf course and TWO disk golf courses - the town is built around 2 large lakes - there is a 5 mile bike path around the lake in town, and a 15 mile path to the lake outside town - with a State Park and an interpretive center (terminal glacier moraines, formation of Minnesota lakes, and 1200 years of indian history.) Friday and Saturdays they have a 75 pax pontoon boat on the lake, with narrator. They also have cross country ski trails in winter.  Lodging 10 blocks away (actually 4 blocks, unless you jump the airport fence!)  We host a number of fly-ins - glider competition, skydiving and aerobatic competitions, so we are set up with water and electricity for camping, toilets available 24 hours in the terminal, as well as showers."', 'type': 'information', 'position': 1, 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-info.svg?v1', 'editVersion': 1, 'createdAt': '2021-01-25T22:53:56+00:00', 'updatedAt': '2021-01-25T22:53:56+00:00'}]}

The airport is almost within town - the west side has 'quiet water' (Minnesotan for 'shallow') used by canoes and Kayaks. We have 7 food places within 4 blocks, two grocery stores, and an auto parts store - we are adjacent to a golf course and TWO disk golf courses - the town is built around 2 large lakes - there is a 5 mile bike path around the lake in town, and a 15 mile path to the lake outside town - with a State Park and an interpretive center (terminal glacier moraines, formation of Minnesota lakes, and 1200 years of indian history.) Friday and Saturdays they have a 75 pax pontoon boat on the lake, with narrator. They also have cross country ski trails in winter. Lodging 10 blocks away (actually 4 blocks, unless you jump the airport fence!) note_default:
The airstrip is located in a remote part of the Panamint Valley in California, it it a BLM owned strip, just west of Death Valley National Park and provides access to a historic mining district on the west side of the valley. In the area are numerous elaborate ruins of the mining era of the region, to include the ruins of Lookout City atop the nearby hill, the Minietta volunteer cabin (open to the public), and many other sites to hike to.

The airstrip should still be considered a more technical and challenging strip due to its overall design; more advanced skills and larger tires are recommended. The airstrip is divided roughly in half by a gully that crosses the strip at its midpoint, creating a strip that is downhill towards its middle. Restoration efforts this time around focused on the northern half of strip north of the gully and resulted in approx. 1150’ of usable runway. The southern half, roughly 900’, was usable before restoration work began. Work this time removed approx. 400’ of overgrowth from the strip and smoothed out that section where car driving had rutted it. This work took place May 2019. The current condition is a rough gravel strip for which larger tires and good prop clearance are advised. Again, work that took place May 2019 that smoothed the central gully to allow safe crossing at a moderate taxi speed. Fly over before landing to ensure runway conditions.

The airstrip is divided roughly in half by a gully that crosses the strip at its midpoint, creating a strip that is downhill towards its middle. Restoration efforts this time around focused on the northern half of strip north of the gully and resulted in approx. 1150’ of usable runway. The southern half, roughly 900’, was usable before restoration work began. Work this time removed approx. 400’ of overgrowth from the strip and smoothed out that section where car driving had rutted it. This work took place May 2019. The current condition is a rough gravel strip for which larger tires and good prop clearance are advised. Again, work that took place May 2019 that smoothed the central gully to allow safe crossing at a moderate taxi speed. Fly over before landing to ensure runway conditions.

The Brodhead Airport (C37) began in January, 1946. It is a privately owned, public use airport. 56 hangars are now on the airport and at nearly 75 airplanes in various stages of construction. The little airport is now known around the country as one of the best grass airports in the midwest and is host to several major fly-ins every year; a Community Pancake Breakfast, a three-day Pietenpol/Hatz convention in July, a private three-day gathering of the Midwest Antique Airplane Club in September and a ski fly-in each February.
Camping is not allowed in between the runways unless there is an event.

\n
\nPilot registration desk northeast of the tie down area next to outhouse. note_default:
Airport is in a large mountain valley with mountainous terrain on all sides. Closest mountainous terrain is about 2 miles North of airport.

Pilot registration desk northeast of the tie down area next to outhouse. Tie down chains are hanging on fence to the north of the tie down area, courtesy car available through locker in bicycle shed. Picnic area is between the tie down area and the first hangar with shelter, table, and fire pit. Fire wood is available in the bike shed. Potable water is available at rear northwest corner of the first hanger. There is a tie down area at the campground, but bring your own tie downs and stakes. Potable water is not available at the campground. There is a walk-through gate in the fence behind the ranger station across from the campground for a shorter route to town from the campground.
You can also connect with Jerome Cain (RAF), 406-461-5631 cell, or email at jcain@theraf.org for conditions at airport and Lincoln Community information.

note_alerts:
Caution if there has been recent moisture, you WILL GET STUCK and rut the airstrip due to the gumbo clay!.
Land on the strip to the North, (Black Butte North, BB0), NOT the old strip to the south, which is closed! The old strip (Black Butte South) is easier to spot than BB0 and is VERY rough due to sage brush. DO NOT land there.
note_default:

Area may have no radio cell coverage

title: Happy Canyon
contact: {'name': 'Utah Backcountry Pilots', 'email': 'Support@UtahBackcountryPilots.org', 'address': None, 'webSite': None, 'phone': '385-220-5313', 'mobile': None, 'cityStateZip': None, 'preferredMethod': {'id': 'email', 'name': 'Email'}}
notes:
{'alert': [{'text': 'Non standard canyon type approaches required

Departure from runway 10 not recommended due to uphill slope and high terrain at departure end.

Pilots should fly in the canyons to the west or to the northeast to come and go from Happy Canyon. Any other direction is not practical due to high terrain. If an aircraft needs to circle to gain altitude, it is recommended to circle north of runway 10/28 due to terrain. There is descending terrain to the west of Happy Canyon airstrip
', 'type': 'alert', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-alert.svg?v1'}, {'text': 'Runway(s) 18 has right hand traffic.', 'type': 'rightRunwayTraffic', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-right-traffic.svg?v1'}, {'text': 'Runway(s) 28 has non standard hand traffic.', 'type': 'nonStandardRunwayTraffic', 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-non-standard-traffic.svg?v1'}], 'default': [{'id': 'a3bf2d26-b07d-4563-96fb-14bac1aa5cb7', 'text': 'There is a historic mining shack at the Happy Canyon airstrip. It contains numerous historic relics, petrified wood, and paraphernalia from early in the last century, almost like a private museum for pilots to enjoy. Use caution in and around the mining shack, as it is old and structurally frail. Please do not remove any of the historic relics and leave them for the next pilot to enjoy. Great airstrip for camping & dark sky stargazing.

Airstrip is leased by UBCP. UBCP requests that no man-made artifacts (drill bits, tools, old household items, etc.) be removed. Emergency water and runway grading tools are in the mining shack.', 'type': 'airportHistory', 'position': 2, 'iconUrl': 'https://api.guide.theraf.org/images/notes/icons/ag-icon-history.svg?v1', 'editVersion': 1, 'createdAt': '2022-05-26T16:11:35+00:00', 'updatedAt': '2022-05-26T16:11:35+00:00'}]}
note_alerts:
Non standard canyon type approaches required

Departure from runway 10 not recommended due to uphill slope and high terrain at departure end.

Pilots should fly in the canyons to the west or to the northeast to come and go from Happy Canyon. Any other direction is not practical due to high terrain. If an aircraft needs to circle to gain altitude, it is recommended to circle north of runway 10/28 due to terrain. There is descending terrain to the west of Happy Canyon airstrip

Runway(s) 18 has right hand traffic.
Runway(s) 28 has non standard hand traffic.
note_default:
There is a historic mining shack at the Happy Canyon airstrip. It contains numerous historic relics, petrified wood, and paraphernalia from early in the last century, almost like a private museum for pilots to enjoy. Use caution in and around the mining shack, as it is old and structurally frail. Please do not remove any of the historic relics and leave them for the next pilot to enjoy. Great airstrip for camping & dark sky stargazing.

Airstrip is leased by UBCP. UBCP requests that no man-made artifacts (drill bits, tools, old household items, etc.) be removed. Emergency water and runway grading tools are in the mining shack.

note_alertsNon standard canyon type approaches required

Departure from runway 10 not recommended due to uphill slope and high terrain at departure end.

Pilots should fly in the canyons to the west or to the northeast to come and go from Happy Canyon. Any other direction is not practical due to high terrain. If an aircraft needs to circle to gain altitude, it is recommended to circle north of runway 10/28 due to terrain. There is descending terrain to the west of Happy Canyon airstrip

Runway(s) 18 has right hand traffic.
